prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: 1mm continuum observations of 102 z=3-5 galaxies
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: short 3.5min integrations of 102 targets located within the 2sqdeg COSMOS field using the standard continuum mode shifted to a higher frequency of 240.0 GHz.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Our chosen observing frequency is the same of for our Cycle 2 project and probes the the restframe 300 - 200 um sub-mm continuum for sources at z=3-6 (i.e. inverted order of redshift bounds), Therefore, ALMA band 6 with a center wavelength of 240GHz is ideal. This is a pure continuum detection experiment and we are using the standard set-up.

The continuum frequency is set to be the same as for the existing Cycle 2 data to allow for direct comparison. The frequency is optimized for sensitivity and probing the rest-frame ~250um sub-mm continuum in our sample.

We request a resolution of 1.5'' similar to the resolution of our Cycle 2 data (with an average beam of 1.7"x1.1"; natural weighting). This translates into a size of ~12kpc that should easily encompass the bulk of the cool gas. Based on high-resolution studies (e.g. Hodge et al. 2012) this is well-matched to typical source sizes of the molecular reservoir (that should strongly dominate the cool gas content as these redshifts; e.g. Obreschkow et al. 2009).

The requested rms is 70uJy to match the new observations to our Cycle 2 data that achieved an rms range of 60-80uJy and resulted in a detection rate of of 50% (44/86) using a limit of S_240GHz > 3sgima. ALMA requires only 3.48min to achieve this rms, e.g. the current IRAM/NOEMA would require >350x more on-source time alone. Based on our empirical calibrations, this means that we will be sensitive to cool gas masses of log(M_gas[M_sun])=10.2(10.6) at 3sigma at a redshift of z=3(5) across our sample. The required sensitivity translates into 3.48min per sources (assuming 36 working antennas) or a total of 9.9h of 12m time to determine the cool gas content and its associated depletion time in a complete sample of 102 massive (log(M_star[M_sun])>10.0) normal star forming (MS) galaxies at redshift z=3-5.
As the properties of our Cycle 3 sample that comprises all massive star forming galaxies at z=3-5 in the COSMOS field that have high quality (flag 3 and 4) spectroscopic redshifts (99 targets) from the VUDS project (see Tasca et al. 2014) amended by 9 galaxies from the ZFOURGE survey to better sample the high stellar mass end (Spitler et al. 2014), we expect a similar number for this sample. The listed flux estimates are only indicative of the detection success given the uncertainties involved in the conversion from SFR to restframe 250um luminosity. Observing the full sample is important to achieve good number statistics across the full redshift range and to sample 1 order of magnitude in stellar mass that will allow us to confirm the trend with stellar mass indicated by our current data. Our analysis of the Cycle 2 data shows that it is apriori not possible to predict the detection success, as our sources are well-mixed in the region of the sSFR vs. stellar mass plane that they occupy.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The evolution of the gas content and gas depletion time beyond redshifts of z=3 is basically unknown for massive (log(M_star/M_sun) > 10.0) normal star-forming, i.e. main sequence, galaxies. This redshift range (z>3) is important the cosmic star formation rate density increases. In Cycle 2 we detected 50% (44/86) of such photo-z selected galaxies in their 240GHz continuum - our proxy for cold gas mass. These z~3.2 objects show no change in gas content and gas depletion time once their location in the main sequence is taken into account. The trend of lower gas depletion times in higher redshift objects continues with a value of 0.4 Gyr at z~3.2. Thus we propose to double our Cycle 2 ALMA sample by observing 102 massive, normal star forming galaxies in the redshift range z=3-5 to (a) extend the redshift range probed, and (b) better sample the low and high stellar mass end. Our sample consists of VUDS galaxies in the COSMOS field with reliable spec-z (93 objects), supplemented by 9 ZFOURGE galaxies in the COSMOS field to better probe the high-mass end. These proposed observations will provide robust constraints vital for current galaxy evolution models.
